### 3. SDC Workflow and New OAuth Parameters
* **Presenter:** Marco Tiloca
* **Draft:** [draft-ietf-ace-workflow-and-params](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-ace-workflow-and-params/)
* **Slides:** [20260720-ace-workflow-and-params](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-ace-20260720-ace-workflow-and-params-00)

#### Discussion:
* This draft formally updates RFC 9200, introducing the alternative Short Distribution Chain (SDC) workflow and adding support for group audience tokens.
* Marco Tiloca highlighted several key updates in version 08:
  * **Dave Robin** provided feedback on parameter phrasing, which was integrated to improve readability.
  * Added clarifications on token revocation (RFC 9770): if the client intends to use token revocation services, it must not opt out of receiving the token or its hash.
  * Corrected the erroneous coupling of client-to-AS and AS-to-client parameters in the SDC workflow.
  * Relocated the EDHOC External Authorization Data (EAD) item from the EDHOC profile draft into this document.
  * **Dynamic Update Failures:** Clarified that when an SDC upload fails because the Resource Server (RS) dropped the old token (and closed the association), the Authorization Server (AS) can establish a new token series "on the fly" to save round trips.
* **Group Audience Upload Failures:** In the current draft, if an AS uploads a token to multiple RSs in a group audience and one fails, the overall transaction fails sequentially. 
  * **Dave Robin** questioned if the sequential "abort-on-first-fail" behavior is too restrictive, suggesting that partial success should be reported so the client can utilize the token for the successful 99% of RSs.
  * **Christian Amsüss** agreed that identifying which RS failed might be overkill but suggested that "abort if one fails" should not be overly prescriptive, as group memberships can dynamically change.
  * Marco Tiloca agreed to explore adding a mechanism or parameter to indicate partial successes to the client.

